250,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-15 12:49:25+00:00,65468547,jd/tenacity,2644,jd,,,176505370,247318711,"No, actually we agree: I think too that special handling for tenacity should not be needed. :)

What you probably do not understand as you said, is why you have to mock `time.sleep` in e.g. Cinder to have things work and why I call that ""papering over the bug"".

Cinder relies on eventlet and its monkey patching of `time.sleep()` (and other functions, such as the `threading` module, etc). In order to change the `time.sleep` function by the version from eventlet – which is what that monkey patching thing is about, you have to call the `eventlet.monkey_patch()` function. What it does is basically:

```py
def monkey_patch():
    import time
    time.sleep = _eventlet_sleep
```

You understand that is this `monkey_patch()` is called _after_ `import tenacity`, well, it's too late. If you do:

```py
import tenacity
eventlet.monkey_patch()
```

Then, once tenacity is imported, the `time.sleep` that is tored in the Retrying kwargs is the standard Python `time.sleep` function. And it's exactly the bug you are hitting right now. The code in Cinder should be changed to be:

```py
eventlet.monkey_patch()
import tenacity
```

And that would solve your issue – no need for mock.

You can see that this behaviour is actually implemented in Cinder command line tools (the way Cinder is ran in real life) here:

https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/cmd/all.py#L28

Now, clearly the unit tests are not doing that correctly: they don't rely on `cinder.cmd.all` to run and the monkey_patch() function is probably called way after tenacity is loaded, this is why you're hitting this bug, and why you have to `mock` to work around it.

My suggestion here is to fix Cinder (and any other project with that bug) by making sure eventlet.monkey_patch() is called *first thing* before importing anything else and running any other code – like in `cinder.cmd.all`.

I hope it's clearer now! :)",{},,User,False
252,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-30 19:30:13+00:00,1079822,jodal/pykka,82534,adamcik,,,92174755,117313995,"Personally I'm not that familiar with Akka, but if I understand the sample code correctly you want to arrange for the message to get sent in x milliseconds. As far as I know Pykka doesn't have any good way of adding this currently.

