423,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-12 18:48:09+00:00,44054354,dabeaz/curio,350836,dabeaz,,,188898831,260140590,"I have pushed a different kind of change that allows two different tasks to read/write on the same file descriptor.  The test code above passes with this change.   The debouncing logic is still being used (but is refined).    I still need to look at the possible case of duplicate file descriptors (reuse) messing things up. 

All of the tests pass, but this would definitely need more hammering on.    The change does NOT allow more than one task to read on the same file or to write on the same file at the same time (i.e., two tasks both expressing an interest in reading).   I'm not exactly sure how common it would be to write code like that. 

That said, do any of the other async frameworks actually allow multiple readers/writers on the same file descriptor?   I looked inside asyncio and it doesn't seem like it would allow such a configuration.    However, I know from operating systems that you can most definitely have multiple threads/processes trying to read/write on the same file descriptor at once.    Maybe there's something interesting for curio to explore there.    I'm not sure.  Just thinking out loud. 
",{},,User,False
