1217,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-05 03:38:35+00:00,1408162,jpadilla/pyjwt,238933,vimalloc,,,219453301,291742431,"One problem you may run into if you go down this route is that you cannot update a token. If you change the expires time of the token, you in essence end up with a totally new token. This means that anyone using your API may have the access token change out from under them on *any* API call (success or failure), and if they are, for example, storing the access tokens in a browsers session storage, they would need to be able to handle this, which adds complexity.

One alternate way you could accomplish the end goal of this would be to instead use two different tokens, an access token and a refresh token. The tokens have some way to differentiate between them, and the access token has any additional information that is needed in your access token, where the refresh token just has the users identity. The access tokens are generally short lived, where the refresh tokens are long lived, and you create an endpoint that users can call out to, which uses their refresh token to generate a new access token. If someone is using your API and gets back an error that the access token has expired, they can simply use the refresh token to generate a new access token, then use retry the request with the new access token.

Besides the reduced complexity, this has the added benefit of if an access token is leaked, it can only be exploited for a short amount of time before it expires (obviously if the refresh token is leaked  it is the same worse case, but as you aren't using the refresh tokens as often there is less surface area for them to be leaked, at least in theory). It also lends itself well to something like a 'freshness' pattern, where tokens generated when authenticating with a username and password are marked as fresh, and can do additional things (such as change passwords, make online payments, etc), that a non-fresh token generated from a refresh token couldn't do without re-confirming the username and password.

I've setup a flask extension that does basically what is outlined above, if you want to see how it might look you could see an example here: http://flask-jwt-extended.readthedocs.io/en/latest/token_freshness.html

This doesn't answer how to do this in pyjwt, but hopefully it gives you some things to think about. Cheers! :)",{},,User,False
