2074,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-01 18:28:54+00:00,3888766,newville/asteval,304251,newville,,,168645302,236665292,"@ankostis Thanks for working on this.   Perhaps it would be better to simply not set a recursion limit at all?  Again, this was added as part of #17, and I'm not really sure how useful it actually is.  Python's own recursion limit might be good enough.  If not, the process creating an  Interpreter() can set that too. 

I might have a few small nits:   I think the various meanings of False and None and the logic around asteval line 102 is a bit arcane.    If kept at all, the recursion limit should default to None, but otherwise really be the actual recursion limit.   Similarly, I think adding to `len(inspect.stack())` is unneeded and likely to cause confusion.

Anyway, why not just drop setting the recursion limit altogether?  
",{},,User,False
