2840,IssueCommentEvent,2016-03-08 09:20:50+00:00,21185133,bw2/ConfigArgParse,931883,dwfreed,,,135076513,193684452,"Because it's a regular arg, the --clear-arg shows up in the help output just like everything else, and the help text for it is simple and concise.  Much more time will be spent on the documentation for the actual merge behavior, since the ConfigArgParse message about multiple locations is pretty clear that later locations override earlier locations.

In my opinion, if we're going to allow merging multiple locations, --clear-arg needs to be there.  Otherwise, how are you going to override a setting stored in a config file or environment variable that you don't want but have no way of changing directly?  For all other actions, later occurrences of an arg automatically override earlier ones in regular argparse, and only append merges, so everything else gets the behavior of --clear-arg for free.  Another example is having an alias that you commonly use, but want to override an append arg in the command line you actually use.

argparse does not allow actions with conflicting args, so if an app already has --clear-arg, and they try to add multisource_merge to --arg, argparse will throw an exception in the codepath handling the add_argument('--arg').  A quick inspection of my implementation would show that the developer could specify any value that evaluates to True except True itself, and --clear-arg will not be added.

Here's my implementation thus far:

https://github.com/dwfreed/ConfigArgParse/tree/multisource-merge

Todo list:
- [ ] Document the merge behavior
- [ ] Apply a sort to the environment variables so that usages of --clear-arg via environment variable actually work deterministically

Notes:

- I made it a boolean because I couldn't think of any other situations beside override (already the default) and merge that aren't too complex",{},,User,False
2841,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-11 23:34:47+00:00,21185133,bw2/ConfigArgParse,6240170,bw2,,,99533480,155944107,"@lahwaacz After thinking about this more, I would prefer (assuming there's broader interest) to add null values rather than add a new / different config-file-loading behavior that would coexist with the current one. Since (as you pointed out) default=""bla.txt"" already works for config file args, that's as far as I currently want to go in this direction.",{},,User,False
