3537,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-18 11:05:04+00:00,29050338,mementum/backtrader,5713511,mementum,,,117527280,157679998,"Trade has been extended:

```python
class Trade(object):
    '''
    Keeps track of the life of an trade: size, price,
    commission (and value?)

    An trade starts at 0 can be increased and reduced and can
    be considered closed if it goes back to 0.

    The trade can be long (positive size) or short (negative size)

    An trade is not meant to be reversed (no support in the logic for it)

    Member Attributes:
      - size (int): current size of the trade
      - price (float): current price of the trade
      - value (float): current value of the trade
      - commission (float): current accumulated commission
      - pnl (float): current profit and loss of the trade (gross pnl)
      - pnlcomm (float):
        current profit and loss of the trade minus commission (net pnl)
      - isclosed (bool):
        records if the last update closed (set size to null the trade
      - isopen (bool): records if any update has opened the trade
      - justopened (bool): if the trade was just opened
      - baropen (int): bar in which this trade was opened
      - dtopen (float): float coded datetime in which the trade was closed
        - Use method ``open_datetime`` to get a Python datetime.datetime
          or use the platform provided ``num2date`` method
      - barclose (int): bar in which this trade was closed
      - dtclose (float): float coded datetime in which the trade was closed
        - Use method ``close_datetime`` to get a Python datetime.datetime
          or use the platform provided ``num2date`` method
      - barlen (int): number of bars this trade was open
    '''
```",{},,User,False
3538,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-01 16:21:39+00:00,29050338,mementum/backtrader,10117812,willhoyle,,,109133564,144777638,"Exactly. How I would like it to work is say, for example, that we're backtesting a 1 minute time frame. 

Time (HH:MM:SS) | Previous Volume | Current Volume | Ratio
------------ | ------------- | ------------- | ------------- |
09:30:00 | 1000 | 2000 | 2 
09:31:00 | 300 | 900 | 3
... | | |
04:00:00 | 300 | 300 | 1  

Our line would hold the ratio values for every minute. In a trading day, there's 6.5 hours * 60 minutes = 390 minutes. So for 1 minute charts you would need a period of 390 in order to 'align' both days.

Maybe something like this:
```python
class RelativeVolume(bt.Indicator):
    alias = ('RVI',)
    lines = ('rvi',)

    params = (
        ('period', 390),
    )

    def __init__(self):
       #not sure if this is the right way to slice data within your framework
       previousvol = self.data.volume[:self.p.period] 
       currentvol = self.data.volume[self.p.period:]
       self.lines.rvi = currentvol/previousvol

        # Done after calc to ensure coop inheritance and composition work
        super(RelativeVolume, self).__init__()
```
The other thing is the period=390 is hard coded to the 1 minute time frame. A time frame of 1 second will yield 23400 candles. At runtime, can the indicator have knowledge of what time frame is being used? Something like:
```python
    timeframe = get_timeframe()
    _adjusted_period = (... calculations to get the approriate period)
    params = (
        ('period', _adjusted_period),
    )
```

There's other problems that might make the logic more complicated than the code above:
 * my data feed might have premarket data, which would cause the lines to not align
 * tick data would cause the same issue since there's a variable number of candles. We could maybe re-sample tick data to an arbitrarily small sampling rate like 0.1 s.

Anyways, this post is getting longer than I thought. Let me know what you think! ",{},,User,False
