3904,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-04 01:28:56+00:00,29613985,jorgebastida/awslogs,3351083,mixja,,,202316918,306011541,"@jorgebastida - I agree it seems impractical to deal with the credentials cache, but until boto3 includes such functionality natively, this approach makes life a lot easier for the user.  Note that the credentials exist per _AWS profile_ not per application.  

As I understand it I'm guessing your workflow is to inject temporary session credentials into your local environment and then run awslogs.  This requires a number of manual steps or custom scripts/utilities (e.g. your aws2fa).

The experience of leveraging the session cache:

```
$ awslogs <cmd> --profile my-mfa-profile
Enter MFA Token: ******
...
...
$ awslogs <cmd> --profile my-mfa-profile
...
...
```

or

```
$ export AWS_PROFILE=my-mfa-profile
$ awslogs <cmd>
Enter MFA Token: ******
...
...
$ awslogs <cmd>
...
...
```

The alternative of Injecting credentials into environment (best case scenario, worst case you have multiple steps before running `awslogs`:

```
$ run_a_custom_script_or_program.blah
Enter MFA Token: ******
$ awslogs <cmd>
...
...
$ awslogs <cmd>
...
...
```

I think by implementing support for the session cache, you make it simpler for the end user (no custom utilities or scripts to deal with).  ",{},,User,False
