4182,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-13 11:07:51+00:00,16787349,workhorsy/py-cpuinfo,2733986,workhorsy,,,255500812,329134877,"Basically there are limitations in the way Pyinstaller works with multiprocessing. So you even with these fixes, you would also have to change the example to be inside a main guard, and freeze support:

```python

# main.py
# Put everything in a main guard or it may execute twice when the process forks 
if __name__ == '__main__':
	import multiprocessing
	import get_cpu_info

	# Call freeze_support or Pyinstaller will recursively fork infinite processes forever
	multiprocessing.freeze_support()
	print(get_cpu_info.get_cpu_info())
```

Then it should work as expected:
```bash
pyinstaller main.py --onefile
```

Once I get this branch done anyway.",{},OWNER,User,False
