5259,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-03 18:34:30+00:00,53352663,ecederstrand/exchangelib,559151,ecederstrand,,,319393661,386394405,Closing. Feel free to re-open if you still have issues with this :-),{},OWNER,User,False
5260,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-30 07:41:03+00:00,53352663,ecederstrand/exchangelib,559151,ecederstrand,,,239423425,312198622,"Yes, I think that's correct. AFAIK, the `Account.contacts` folder only contains the contacts that were created by the user. To access the global address book, which is what most business users refer to as the address book, we'll need to solve #93.",{},,User,False
5261,IssueCommentEvent,2017-08-15 11:25:24+00:00,53352663,ecederstrand/exchangelib,559151,ecederstrand,,,250054741,322442715,"`ResolveNames` hasn't received much love, so I think this is an open question. We only use it internally as part of the initial connection setup.

EWS returns an error message, so I think that we should also convey that this is an error condition. Also, I dislike methods sometimes returning single items, sometimes lists of items.

I'd prefer if we expand `exchangelib.errors. ErrorNameResolutionMultipleResults` so it can hold the multiple results. So users would write something like (this is pseudocode):

```python
for elem in ResolveNames(account.protocol).call(unresolved_entries=some_names):
    if isinstance(elem, ErrorNameResolutionMultipleResults):
        print([res for res in elem.results])
    else:
        print(elem)
```

Also, I'm curious what your use case is for this. Most services have a shortcut method on the account or folder, to ease setup and return nice class instances. Maybe `ResolveNames` needs that, too?",{},,User,False
5262,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-30 14:05:59+00:00,53352663,ecederstrand/exchangelib,195099,007,,,353578480,417331646,"From a security perspective, I don't want to ship more libraries to a production instance than I have to. Reducing any possible attack surface is [basic security practice](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attack_surface), [OWASP recommended](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Attack_Surface_Analysis_Cheat_Sheet), and even [Microsoft-approved](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-defender-exploit-guard/attack-surface-reduction-exploit-guard).

There have been [125 CVEs](https://www.cvedetails.com/vulnerability-list/vendor_id-42/product_id-61/MIT-Kerberos.html) against Kerberos, so it's not exactly a safe package to add without considering the trade-offs in functionality. The problem is that there is no functionality - adding the potential vulnerabilities gets me zero additional features, just maybe a bugfix or two in this package.

As it stands, Kerberos is dead weight. We're stuck on the N-1 version until we can ditch that weight, or until the features justify the potential security complications.",{},NONE,User,False
