5619,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-01 14:35:05+00:00,3687291,maxcountryman/flask-login,899110,Bastian-Kuhn,,,230008501,305512431,"Sure,
the App tries the following request
```
GET /auth/?has_age=True HTTP/1.1
Host: my-domain.de
x-forwarded-host: www.hpe.com
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.3; WOW64; rv:53.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/53.0 Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8 Accept-Language: en-US,en;q=0.5
Referer: https://my-domain.de/?next=%2F
Cookie: session=XXX
```

And the servers (cause of flask_login) response is:
```
HTTP/1.1 302 FOUND
Server: nginx
Date: Tue, 30 May 2017 21:27:24 GMT
Content-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 209
Connection: close
Location: https://www.hpe.com/
Set-Cookie: session=XXX;
Secure; HttpOnly; Path=/
Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=63072000; includeSubdomains;
X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN
X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
Cache-Control: private, max-age=0, s-maxage=0
```

That can reproduced in chrome with the extension requestly.
The x-forwarded-host: www.hpe.com is the problem here, and i don't see a good way to block this in nginx. I disagree with some of the Issues of this tool, but the part that flask login directly uses information based on host headers are right. On the other hand, yes this has to happen on the client PC, since the connection is encrypted. But this fact doesn't count for this tool. ",{},,User,False
