5983,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-20 17:09:52+00:00,68146968,vimalloc/flask-jwt-extended,238933,vimalloc,,,230151619,302886165,"Basically because of how decorators work, you are creating a new function there which takes get_jwt_identity() as a parameter, and returns a new function based on that. This is calling get_jwt_identity() only once, and returning a new function that has the results of get_jwt_identity as the first argument. Since this was called outside of a requests, it returns an empty value here (Side note, I meant for that get_jwt_identity() called outside of a request to return None, not {}, I'll fix that up later today). The get_jwt_identity() function isn't getting called every request like you would expect, as the end result is method1 gets changed to basically a new function, then that new function gets called at every request.

There are blogs out there which explain this in much better detail then I can, perhaps checkout this: https://realpython.com/blog/python/primer-on-python-decorators/ (just the first one I found when googling). If you have questions about that, you can hit me up and I will try my best to answer them.

As for fixing it up, do you have access to the service_supported code? If you put the get_jwt_identity() in there, it should work how you expect. An example decorator might look something like this:

```python
def service_supported(fn, service_type):
    @wraps(fn)
    def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):
        username =str(get_jwt_identity())
        user = UserObject(username=username)
        if not user.supports_service(service_type):
            raise Exception(""User does not support this service"")
        return fn(*args, **kwargs)
    return wrapper
```

Hope this helps :)",{},,User,False
