6717,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-29 10:30:51+00:00,744916,gem/oq-engine,496400,g-weatherill,316546,gem,292344523,361203618,"The problem, insofar as I've been able to discern, is due to the switching between spherical and cartesian coordinate systems. Certain configurations of plane and/or location can mean that when you generate a feasible plane in spherical coordinates, it can become distorted when translated to planar a planar system. I've encountered this a couple of times, which are both relevant for your case studies:

1. In UCERF the planes were built from fault sections that were projected down dip. However, rather than using the continuous mesh (the ""Stirling method"" that OpenQuake uses) UCERF builds its sources as planar faults for each section. The problem comes when you get a fault segment that is very short (say < 1 - 2km) but is then projected at a dip shallower than 90 degrees. Then the inclined fault plane is much wider than it is longer (maybe 15 - 17 km down dip and < 1 km along strike), and it seems that when this is projected into the cartesian system it does not define a plane according to OQs checks. Unfortunately, this occurs on a couple of faults in UCERF in which a small < 1 - 2 km ""kink"" at the end of certain dipping faults produces these types of very short segments.

2. The second case I encountered was for large ruptures at very high latitudes, which is probably why this is affecting the Canada model! I think here the problem is that as you get closer to the pole the potential distortion grows when translating to a cartesian system when the distance between points is large.

Honestly, I don't think there is a solution to this other than to switch off the planar correctness checks, or massively relax them, under certain conditions such as those labelled above.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
