6850,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-12 04:59:22+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,2498805,rhelmot,12520807,angr,201639911,307690169,"- The people who were supposed to do the IoT analysis project have been suspiciously silent in terms of bugging me about things not working, so those probably are not being worked on.
- Yeah, that is something that was brought up at FOSDEM - the valgrind devs hate ccalls just as much as we do. libvex actually tries to remove all the ccalls it possibly can in the optimization step - individual ccalls have ""flatten to IR"" functions which try to remove them. I don't think that would work in this case, but in the future we should avoid ccalls as the solution to our problems where possible...

Another solution could potentially be to extend the IR to have a ""load"" command which additionally lets you specify a memory region. This would be pretty nasty and invasive to the memory model, but it would be totally correct as far as I'm aware.",{},,User,False
6851,IssueCommentEvent,2017-08-29 04:57:30+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,3453847,zardus,12520807,angr,249037879,325555290,"I think this still has a few issues:

- It doesn't handle the case when there is no newline (i.e., the file ends).
- It concretizes the length of the read in all circumstances.

I think the second issue can be resolved by calling out to the `read` procedure (or to `state.posix.read(fd, dst, length)`), which handles symbolic read lengths. The first one is a bit trickier, though, and needs some thought...",{},,User,False
