7320,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-28 16:02:40+00:00,49615802,pypa/auditwheel,641278,rmcgibbo,647025,pypa,239083677,311706738,"I don't think this is a good idea.

The big idea in the manylinux1 spec is that you can't ship shared libraries that have ELF-level dependencies on other `.so` files not included in the wheel (beyond the ones that all supported linux distros are guaranteed to have).

My understanding is that you explicitly don't want this. You want a shared library in turbodc to have an ELF-level dependency on a shared library that it doesn't ship (one that pyarrow ships). In my mind, that makes it not manylinux1-compatible.

Obviously there's nothing to stop anyone from retagging non-manylinux1 wheels as manylinux1. PyPI doesn't run auditwheel to verify the accuracy of the tag when you upload a wheel, it just reads whatever tag it finds in the wheel and trusts it. And that's good.

But I'm -1 on adding features to auditwheel, in its capacity as the ""PyPA-blessed manylinux1 retagging tool"", whose explicit purpose is to create wheels that are incorrectly labeled as manylinux1 and don't conform to PEP 513. That's exactly what a whitelist would do. It seems like a big footgun to me.",{},,User,False
7321,IssueCommentEvent,2016-07-18 12:53:37+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,166050177,233319823,"I also just ran ez_setup.py and it worked just fine.

