7997,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-22 06:58:00+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,3019665,jakirkham,6392739,conda,230065974,303015020,"Totally a fan of key/value with features, @kalefranz. We tried to do something like this with our `blas` package, but I don't think it totally fixes the issue. Expect some enhancements on the `conda`/`conda-build` front should be able to though.

<hr>

As for `mkl`...

We don't really have a way to include `mkl` in conda-forge ATM. This would require development packages and such, which we don't have. However it does seem Intel has made an effort to put these in their channel recently.

The other issue is this indemnification clause in Intel's license agreement. As an open source project with no funds, conda-forge can't really promise to pay Intel's legal fees in case someone tries to sue them for some issues caused by some package(s) we might build with `mkl`. There is the other question of whether we would even want to be in that situation if we did have funds to cover such a thing.

As it stands, we have tended to shy away from including `mkl` in conda-forge. This seems to be a typical response of other OSS projects distributing binaries. For instance NumPy and SciPy go to great lengths to not use `mkl` or Intel compilers when it comes to their wheels for Windows. If Intel was willing to drop this indemnification clause for open source projects, I think it would help adoption of `mkl` in a larger arena. Though I get the impression this is unlikely to happen.

That said, if someone either does not install or uninstalls our `blas` package, it appears to revert back to `mkl` packages from `defaults`. So this seems to be sufficient for those packages in `defaults`. I guess those not in `defaults` that could be built with `mkl` could be rebuilt and added to `defaults` if there is sufficient demand.",{},,User,False
