9133,IssueCommentEvent,2015-02-05 05:23:51+00:00,10247874,docker/docker-py,75556,gtaylor,5429470,docker,55924899,72996168,"Not entirely your particular set of symptoms, but I was playing around with pull() on my own and noticed that passing in an invalid image/tag results in something like this:

```
Status Code: 200

{""status"":""Pulling repository blartyblartyblarty""}
{""errorDetail"":{""message"":""Error: image library/blartyblartyblarty: not found""},""error"":""Error: image library/blartyblartyblarty: not found""}
```

A look at the [Docker API docs](http://docs.docker.com/reference/api/docker_remote_api_v1.15/#create-an-image) showed that sure enough, only 200 or 500 are listed as probable response codes. On the docker-py side, [raise_for_status()](https://github.com/docker/docker-py/blob/master/docker/client.py#L96) is being called correctly, but the Docker API is sending a 200 (meaning no exception is raised).

It might be worth checking and seeing if you are actually getting an HTTP 200 instead of a 403, even though the body is saying 403. I may be way off on this, but figured I'd share a somewhat related experience.",{},,User,False
