9445,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-03 00:50:38+00:00,82729529,google/python-fire,892765,dbieber,1342004,google,337526286,410110734,"Hi, I think this is an issue with how you're using elasticsearch, not an issue with Python Fire.
From the error message you posted, it looks like the snapshot.restore function in elasticsearch doesn't accept None as a value for ""params"". It expects a dict for params. To resolve this, change your function like so:

```
def restore_snapshot(self, repository, snapshot, body=None, params=None):
  params = params or {}
  response = self.es_client.snapshot.restore(repository, snapshot, body=body, params=params)
  print(response.status_code)
  print(response.text)
```",{},MEMBER,User,False
