9645,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-19 17:10:08+00:00,72477752,pulumi/pulumi,1871912,swgillespie,21992475,pulumi,333460905,398474783,">  More important is a simple an idiomatic API design that works nicely for both Python 2 and Python 3 users.

Yeah, that's sort of what I was getting it (in a really unclear way). `asyncio` was a huge paradigm shift in Python I/O and it's only available to Python 3. `tornado` exists and has a similar-enough API surface area that it could probably stand-in for `asyncio` with a little bit of abstraction. I'm sure that we're not the only people who have this problem so perhaps there's even a library out there that does this already.

>  Not sure - will depend a lot on the details of the proposed API design for outputs (I assume that is where we are imagining async/await might become relevant?).

Outputs are part of it, but I think the core of the question is: does Python block every time it interacts with the engine? If not, what sort of interface do we present to Python code? Twisted (all Pythons), asyncio (> Python 3.4), and `concurrent.futures` (> Python 3.2, backported to Python 2) all provide implementations of a Future class which we could use for this sort of thing, but each one is slightly different from the other and it's going to take some thought to figure out what to do so that we can play nicely with Python 2 while still allowing people to `await` a Future in Python 3.5 or above.
",{},MEMBER,User,False
