9689,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-07 20:14:37+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,4459524,jagerman,17565521,pybind,175565887,245402534,Updated with a better fix for non-referenceable types.  I *think* it's correct to disallow `py::cast<T>(o)` where T is a reference or pointer for any type except `type_caster_generic`-derived types (since those hold pointers to objects stored somewhere elsewhere).,{},,User,False
9690,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-22 12:28:30+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,4831417,dean0x7d,17565521,pybind,223545669,296369959,"You need to release Python's GIL before calling back to Python from C++ threads. See the [Global Interpreter Lock](http://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/master/advanced/misc.html#global-interpreter-lock-gil) in the docs.

Essentially, `call_parallel` needs `py::gil_scoped_release`. The `py::gil_scoped_acquire` part is usually taken care of automatically, e.g. the `PYBIND11_OVERLOAD` macro and the `std::function` casters always acquire the GIL before calling Python functions. It's just the GIL release part that needs to be done explicitly when threads are spawned in C++.",{},,User,False
