10332,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-21 13:52:33+00:00,35690635,astropy/regions,2772384,bmatthieu3,847984,astropy,339882208,414681566,"@cdeil - Currently the code is in the branch MOCSkyRegion of the MOCPy repo : https://github.com/cds-astro/mocpy/tree/MOCSkyRegion and consists of two files each containing one class:
* The interval_set.IntervalSet class describing the internal struct of a MOC.
* The moc.MOC class describing the MOC object (API [here](https://mocpy.readthedocs.io/en/mocskyregion/api.html) involving differents methods : union, difference, intersection, contains). Of course I can put these two files here.

I have some questions regarding the implementation in the regions API : 

* As I can see I should create a new MOCSkyRegion and MOCPixelRegion classes inherited from SkyRegion (.resp PixelRegion). Do you know examples, e.g. PRs that could guide me for implementing a new region type ?

* Should I move the code inside the mocpy.MOC and interval_set.IntervalSet classes into those two classes or should we use MOCPy directly as a PIP dependency and define a mocpy.MOC object as an attribute of the future MOCSkyRegion class ? 
I was just thinking we will need to put astropy-healpix as a dependency of regions as MOCs are heavily using it.

* We do not plot MOCs using matplotlib patches but by sampling the sky and determine whether each of these samples lies into the HEALPix cells of the MOC.Then I use [pcolormesh](https://matplotlib.org/gallery/images_contours_and_fields/pcolormesh_levels.html) to color pixels lying into the MOC with one color, and those who do not with an other color. I have seen PixelRegion has a plot method using mpl patches that is why I say that.
",{},NONE,User,False
