10756,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-01 04:58:50+00:00,23984796,jupyter/nbgrader,83444,jhamrick,7388996,jupyter,301250452,369474337,"Yes, this is definitely something we plan to add, see #799

In the meantime though this should be pretty straightforward to do yourself by writing a [custom exporter](http://nbgrader.readthedocs.io/en/stable/plugins/export-plugin.html). Here is a more detailed example of how to [extract information from the gradebook](http://nbgrader.readthedocs.io/en/stable/user_guide/advanced.html#getting-information-from-db). You can combine these two examples by essentially taking the code from the latter link and putting it in the `export` method of the plugin.

And, in particular, if you want to compute things like the average score per assignment per question there are a lot of methods the gradebook object supports for doing things like this. For example, there is [`average_notebook_score`](http://nbgrader.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api/gradebook.html#nbgrader.api.Gradebook.average_notebook_score) which gives the average score for a notebook in an assignment. See here for a full list of all gradebook functions: http://nbgrader.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api/gradebook.html

There isn't a good way for excluding particular questions from overall grades, and this is likely something we will not support officially in nbgrader---but it is again something you could write a custom exporter for (though you'd have to loop over all cells and compute the total score manually, rather than using a predefined gradebook method).",{},OWNER,User,False
10759,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-29 17:38:39+00:00,23984796,jupyter/nbgrader,83444,jhamrick,7388996,jupyter,173601614,243196127,"I think for the most part it works pretty well. One suggestion might be to have the default login url just be `'/hub/login'` (rather that including the full url at the beginning) because otherwise the `?next=...` redirection doesn't work (since JupyterHub will refuse absolute redirects, only relative ones).",{},,User,False
