11032,IssueCommentEvent,2016-07-28 15:54:37+00:00,8463294,mozilla/treeherder,501702,edmorley,131524,mozilla,162815016,235939043,"PR updated with the following changes:
* Removed the maintenance page (that couldn't be bypassed) and replaced it with a maintenance information overlay (see screenshot in previous comment) that can be dismissed the same as the shortcuts help overlay.
* The permissions.py based approach of blocking requests that are making changes (ie anything but GET/HEAD/OPTIONS) has been replaced with a custom middleware approach, since the latter also protects against Django admin changes and is much simpler.
* I've added an explicit test for the HTTP 503 maintenance behaviour, and just skipped any other tests that fail due to not being able to submit, rather than make the PR hard to read with 100s of changes. (Even more tests otherwise needed fixing than in the last version of the PR, since the middleware approach is more complete at blocking).

A way to test:
* Run `./mange.py runserver` but with master checked out
* Open http://local.treeherder.mozilla.org
* Log into the local instance
* Only then update the Git checkout to this branch (and don't refresh the loaded UI)
* Then try eg retriggers and check that the UX is ok (this emulates eg a sheriff who has the UI open already when we do the deploy of this branch, and so won't initially see the maintenance banner)
* Then refresh the UI to see the maintenance banner

Limitations:
* Until bug 1290082 is fixed, not all UI actions that make requests will correctly display the full server maintenance message.
* The perf pages don't display the overlay, since they haven't been fitted with the keyboard shortcuts overlay. I don't think it's worth the effort hooking that up for the sake of a 30 min maintenance window, given the perfherder people are more advanced users who will inevitably already know about the maintenance, and who will likely already load/refresh the Treeherder homepage if they try making perfherder changes and requests fail.",{},,User,False
11039,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-03 17:50:46+00:00,8463294,mozilla/treeherder,294864,jgraham,131524,mozilla,319978200,386380528,"To avoid getting cross-test matches i.e. where we classify a failure from test A against an intermittent in test B. That's not necessarily always the right thing especially in cases where the subtest name can change or the same intermittent applies to a group of related tests, but it was intended as a conservative approach to only classify things where we had a-priori confidence that there could be a match.

In any case I think we should be looking to use this data as a feature to match on, even if we don't require an exact match.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
