11252,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-01 23:34:13+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,239726,scottpurdy,1039191,numenta,167147223,236741548,"I think the idea here is:

1. The raw score calculation is specific to temporal memory in general, but not any specific version so we leave it in `nupic.algorithms.anomaly` and if you have an instance of TM, you can pass the active/predicted columns to that function to get a raw score. This is the same as before.
2. The anomaly likelihood isn't specific to TM. It lives separately in `nupic.algorithms.anomaly_likelihood` with a class to maintain the state. There are other ideas for refactoring this discussed here (#3228) and for later consideration. This is the same as before.
3. Others (@breznak) have wanted to experiment with other algorithms. The original take on this (the [anomaly class](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/99d8b7470993d338090c414fe0dd98a24923feea/src/nupic/algorithms/anomaly.py#L56)) had two downsides. It required that people get their algorithms merged into NuPIC in order to use. And it tried to create a common interface for algorithms that had different parameters and required different state. We decided it would be better to have separate regions so people could experiment with their own algorithms simply by creating their own region. The only implementation that has been shown useful in NuPIC is the version proposed here (compute raw score and then likelihood). We'd love to see people experiment with other implementations and it should be easier now that they can use the pluggable Network API interface. Or if you don't like the Network API then don't use it, it isn't required since all of the NuPIC anomaly logic is in the raw score function and the likelihood class that can be used (or not) as you please.
4. We want to remove the Anomaly class and other algorithms that are speculative. We added them before because we didn't have any other way for @breznak to experiment with different versions. We could put the Anomaly class into a deprecated state. That seems like slowly ripping off a band aid though.

@breznak - Are you asking that we keep `Anomaly` and `AnomalyRegion`, deprecate them for some time before removing, or something else?",{},,User,False
11253,IssueCommentEvent,2015-01-10 10:35:29+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,2166111,breznak,1039191,numenta,53526841,69451372,"@scottpurdy Thanks for helping out with experimenting with this idea.. 
>  I am also skeptical that swarming on model runtime speed will be useful. 

I can't tell without trying, but I believe it would, in some cases. Eg. I've seen a model where 1024 cols. was enough, but 4096 cols had tiny performance top, but visibli slower in processing time. This metric is to help this issue. 

> You mention it as a secondary metric but we don't have any way to have a secondary metric as far as I know.

True, this can be useful only as a secondary metric, that's why I created #1710 which should basically be weighted sum of other metrics, eg: `0.3*speedMetric + 0.7*altMAPE` 
",{},,User,False
