11817,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-24 12:48:28+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,64938,ants,1564818,zalando,184253903,255730694,"Supporting dynamic config changes is one todo I forgot to write up. Seems straightforward enough.

I'm not sure about having mode=disabled, it's certainly safer from unexpected behavior. On the other hand, all the distros I have seen would require you to explicitly assign permissions anyway. Having to change the config adds an extra step. I have a systemd unit here that makes enabling watchdog support as easy as `systemctl enable patroni-watchdog`.

I did some research into how to reliably detect PostgreSQL shut down without having to wait for the shutdown checkpoint to complete. This is mostly relevant for demote('offline') case, as we need to hold off watchdog keepalives until PostgreSQL has completed shutdown process to the point that no backends survive, but having to wait for checkpointer to complete shutdown checkpoint would quite likely result in a reboot due to timeout. Doing an immediate shutdown wouldn't be much of an improvement from a usability standpoint. Postmaster state machine actually has a state for the specific condition we need here, but unfortunately I don't think there is any way to check this state from the outside. I guess polling the postmaster child processes and classifying them based on their command line would work, but seems somewhat fragile. ",{},,User,False
