12036,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-13 06:16:46+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,304637882,372558427,"Sometimes solutions or proofs of non-solutions to combinatorial problems can be very difficult to find. 
For example, if you encoding the following problem into propositional satisfiability: 

             fit N pigeons into M holes, no hole may contain two pigeons.

Alternatively, you have a shoe closet and your shoes are very fashionable, so you are only willing to fit one shoe per shelf in the closet. You ahve N shoes and M shelves. 

If you set N = M + 1, the problem is unsolvable. If you have N <= M, the problem is solvable.
The time taking to find solutions for N <= M tends to be really quick. 
The time taking to find solutions for N > M, especially for N = M + 1, can be extremely high for SAT solvers.

Similarly, the integer solver may struggle when seemingly similar problem are easy. 
This holds particularly for problems that you create using a random problem. Z3 is not at all a solver for randomly generated problems. 
",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
