12871,IssueCommentEvent,2015-12-21 20:48:02+00:00,2843531,4teamwork/ftw.upgrade,405124,lukasgraf,681821,4teamwork,123315070,166414099,"Without having looked into the the details of how to implement this, I'd say I could well imagine including such functionality in `ftw.upgrade`.

We'll have to see what @jone thinks once he's back.

One thing to consider though is that `ftw.upgrade` doesn't really deal with QuickInstaller products, but only GenericSetup profiles. We did include some code to avoid surprising effects where upgrade steps for products that had been uninstalled through quickinstaller were still listed (see #46 and PR #55). But that's about all that `ftw.upgrade` knows about quickinstaller, otherwise it just deals with GS profiles.

> I guess the alternative is that if I want to install new package B I can write an upgrade step for an already installed package A that does this. But that feels a bit 'meh' to me.

That's exactly what we've been doing so far. After all, if you want a reproducible setup, you'll need to introduce a dependency on that package's profile from some sort of policy profile anyway, right? And we usually then include an upgrade step in that policy that simply installs the profile for the new package. From then on, all changes beyond the initial installation are tracked as upgrade steps in the new package.

But still, I can see use cases where this would be quite handy.",{},,User,False
