13813,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-12 14:34:52+00:00,2113510,crossbario/autobahn-python,3714876,rdebroiz,5656948,crossbario,303619191,372330727,"I was going to say that a hint in the doc and the example that it's the user's responsibility to yield if needed to the event loop in `detail.progress`  would have helped me. 

It's kind of already there. Maybe a comment to emphasize this point would be great:
```python
# In autobahn-python/examples/asyncio/wamp/rpc/progress/backend.py

        async def longop(n, details=None):
            if details.progress:
                for i in range(n):
                    details.progress(i)
                     # Yield to the loop here, 
                     # otherwise it will block until all `details.progress` calls 
                     # has been done. 
                    await asyncio.sleep(1)
```
Also what confused me, I think, is that it's not needed  for `on_progress`, The event loop got the hand back after each call of `on_progress` even if you don't explicitly yield to it. It would be good to have the same behavior on both side.",{},NONE,User,False
