14316,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-30 20:13:32+00:00,17689377,pre-commit/pre-commit,1810591,asottile,6943086,pre-commit,269735118,340569866,"pip (setuptools / wheels) doesn't provide options for writing files outside of the installation directory, and even with that I think that being explicit is much better.

If you work in an enterprise environment where modifying the default `git` templates is an option, you could include the pre-commit hook template there.

One option that I've used with good success is adding `pre-commit install` to common tasks in the repository such as in `tox`'s tests, in `make test`, etc. (whatever common entry point you have to ""setting up a development environment"").  Here's [an example](https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks/blob/e718847ccbc65cd72a89fefb4db61c55ec4d430d/tox.ini#L18)

Another option is to include `pre-commit` as part of your continuous integration, here's [our documentation on this](http://pre-commit.com/#usage-in-continuous-integration).

Yet another option is to include `pre-commit` as part of server side hooks (`pre-receive`, etc.) such that it is enforced server side.",{},OWNER,User,False
