14482,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-30 20:09:42+00:00,1199632,schematics/schematics,426889,edc,7866441,schematics,51726674,160744941,"I might not have a full picture of the issues at play, but based on my limited understanding, I feel the solution presented here is a bit heavy. My earlier comment was more of a selfish attempt to isolate backward-incompatible changes so my work does not get interrupted. I've since given it a little more thought.

Please correct me if I am wrong. I think there are two separate issues:

1. The concept of ""partial"". Using a Model to represent a partial is the culprit of many issues such as unexpected/undesired behavior about default values. Things get weird when Model tries to serve two distinct purposes.

2. The semantic of setting `None` value on a field. Currently, it means to remove any existing value on a field, and the immediately side effect of falling back to default on the field.

I tend to think these are two separate issues that require attention to their root causes. Putting more options to the constructor or `import_loop` may stop the bleeding, at the cost of unnecessary complexity, IMHO.

What do think about these ideas?

1. Make Partial a first class citizen separate from the Model. When a Model class is created, automatically create a sibling class for the Partial. For example, if a `Customer` model class is created, `Customer.Partial` is the class to be used to work with partial data. Partial obviously does not do validation or anything beyond converting data, and does not respect default values, etc. It shares schema definition with its mother class, and nothing more than that. I believe its use case is limited to parsing HTTP PATCH data.

2. Cleaning up the behavior of field default values, by modeling it after structs in static typing languages like C and [Swift](https://developer.apple.com/library/prerelease/ios/documentation/Swift/Conceptual/Swift_Programming_Language/Initialization.html). (I think a schema is basically a struct in Python.) In these languages, a default is *only* used during initialization/instantiation. After an object has been constructed and initialized, default values on fields are never used. I believe this fits our mental model much better and I would be surprised if any tests will break under this model. ",{},,User,False
