Reviewed 2 of 2 files at r2.
Review status: all files reviewed at latest revision, 3 unresolved discussions.

---

*[jsonapi_requests/orm/api_model.py, line 158 at r1](https://reviewable.io:443/reviews/socialwifi/jsonapi-requests/33#-L0EtLQtxrpoMby54fWj:-L0P7hyv0m_ScN11XJLg:b-n86wff) ([raw file](https://github.com/socialwifi/jsonapi-requests/blob/5791b7f1635f588bc3c64572780726ef091779a4/jsonapi_requests/orm/api_model.py#L158)):*
<details><summary><i>Previously, thomaxxl (Thomas Pollet) wrote…</i></summary><blockquote>

The spec has the following to say regarding deleting resources:
<quote>
Responses
202 Accepted
If a deletion request has been accepted for processing, but the processing has not been completed by the time the server responds, the server MUST return a 202 Accepted status code.

204 No Content
A server MUST return a 204 No Content status code if a deletion request is successful and no content is returned.

200 OK
A server MUST return a 200 OK status code if a deletion request is successful and the server responds with only top-level meta data.

404 NOT FOUND
A server SHOULD return a 404 Not Found status code if a deletion request fails due to the resource not existing.

Other Responses
A server MAY respond with other HTTP status codes.

A server MAY include error details with error responses.

A server MUST prepare responses, and a client MUST interpret responses, in accordance with HTTP semantics. 
</quote>


Not sure what I should do in case of a 202 either
I may do something like this:

```
def delete(self):
        api_response = self.endpoint.delete(object=self.raw_object)
        if api_response.status_code in (200, 202, 204):
            # successfully deleted
            self.raw_object = None
       else: ...???
```

But I don't understand what the raw_object is/does either so I might not really be qualified to change this code. (just wanted the delete functionality added) . The code could use some more documentation too (what does the api.registry do for example? seems interesting but I don't find any docs). 
</blockquote></details>

Basically `raw_object` is the store(cache) for objects attributes, after successful delete,
we need to update the raw_object with proper data (in this situation the object is deleted, so there should be no data)

If we wouldn't do it, accessing any deleted object attribute, will search the raw object for this attribute and it will find it, because it the raw_object wasn't ""synced"" during the delete.

Also keep in mind the lazy nature od this library, accessing object's attributes causes requests only if the attribute wasn't found in the `raw_object` or when explicitly calling `refresh()`.

We are planing to add comprehensive documentation in near future.

