14682,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-18 15:42:28+00:00,66363927,zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient,655674,Tam-Lin,21196715,zhmcclient,200481235,273510648,"I'll have to take this up with the HMC API folks, I guess.  I agree that's what the footnote says, but it seems to contradict the description column, which says it will return 0 if ""The object-id does not represent a logical partition with at least one shared general purpose processor.""  So the description column says an LPAR  without at least one shared GP will return 0, but the footnote says that the same LPAR will return a Null value.",{},,User,False
14683,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-06 12:29:21+00:00,66363927,zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient,8939758,andy-maier,21196715,zhmcclient,172686272,277667364,"Addressed Juergen's comments from aug 26 as follows:

1. Name of `hmc_extract.py` script:

   > For my understanding the hmc_extract.py script is a script to get the inventory of all resources managed by the zHMC. I would propose to rename the script to get_inventory.py.

   Its main purpose is not to get an inventory, but to create an HMC info file. So I renamed it to `create_hmcinfo.py`.

2. `zhmcclient/_tests` directory:

   > I don't like that we put any test code into the zhmcclient source folder like the `_tests` folder. We should separate source and test code.

   I moved its content (the `_hmcinfo.py` file) into the `tests/function` directory which is a package anyway because py.test requires that. The only drawback is now that it needs to be imported from `tests.function`, which can be confused with a Python package named `test`. Note that relative imports are allowed only from within a package, and the scripts that need this module are not modules in packages.",{},,User,False
