15126,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-23 20:18:36+00:00,71996613,blue-yonder/tsfresh,96679,earthgecko,6234170,blue-yonder,307637201,375786548,"## The pros and cons (and notebooks what about them?)

So adding travis_wait ```travis_wait 20 python setup.py test``` makes a bit of a difference, however it comes at a price.

And the Python-3.5.2 build still failed on

```
[gw1] FAILED tests/integrations/test_notebooks.py::NotebooksTestCase::test_basic_pipeline_example 
```

For reference build jobs py2 - https://travis-ci.org/blue-yonder/tsfresh/jobs/357545569 and py3 - https://travis-ci.org/blue-yonder/tsfresh/jobs/357545570

### cons

1. You lose the real time output in the Travis jobs page.  Basically Travis spits out ALL the output only at the end in one big paste and for the whole job just sits on


```
The command ""sed -i 's/\-n auto/\-n 2/g' setup.cfg"" exited with 0.
$ if [ $TRAVIS_PULL_REQUEST == false ] && ! [ $TRAVIS_BRANCH == 'master' ]; then py.test tests/units -n2; else travis_wait 20 python setup.py test; fi
```

Then jumps to 

```
================== 227 passed, 14 warnings in 526.73 seconds ===================
/home/travis/.travis/job_stages: line 169:  3473 Terminated              travis_jigger $! $timeout $cmd
The command ""if [ $TRAVIS_PULL_REQUEST == false ] && ! [ $TRAVIS_BRANCH == 'master' ]; then py.test tests/units -n2; else travis_wait 20 python setup.py test; fi"" exited with 0.
cache.2
store build cache
0.01s
33.66schange detected (content changed, file is created, or file is deleted):
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/0/1/5/1/0/01510501120df000abad3969c9311e384214fa17d7027ef95bf91707
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/0/4/6/f/2/046f263a04464ad173f2b55b53089d6611b281fd92901c6030b4cd93
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/0/5/1/d/d/051ddbcfada687fb27df4b43966167a67f6706da37bcbb89d2838836
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/0/6/0/7/b/0607bfec44b45165c2faff761ccac99a98d9fd850746c7745c710bfa
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/0/c/5/e/4/0c5e4121c33711c362362e34cc3a3697cef22b9e6f74a0440131f791
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/0/e/7/b/9/0e7b99547a0247a24df2175f35e166cf96f0194417e99b4851dbf306
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/1/7/b/b/4/17bb4c359c58b8944aba924db1f952f1ebf83975f86088985f70f836
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/1/8/a/f/f/18affb199964ddd5181e75313e322994f424d8d77b78d0192a7e0d15
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/1/8/d/e/0/18de0670993434c1d60d77f59723689f00d0e2e81d36e0202f1f6459
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/1/b/b/d/e/1bbde7f10876562f138fa536953ad413bfc645c4f5f79dd4f103eae5
/home/travis/.cache/pip/http/2/1/8/a/6/21
...
changes detected, packing new archive
.
.
.
.
uploading archive
after_success
1.99s$ coveralls
Submitting coverage to coveralls.io...
Coverage submitted!
Job #1339.1
https://coveralls.io/jobs/34948709
Done. Your build exited with 0.
```
2. You lose the green PASSED and red FAILED - in the single output there is NO colour, which is pretty shit as when you want to know which of the 227 tests FALIED, it is easy to find in red.

3. It seems to lose the timeout or error messages one has come to expect.

```
tests/integrations/test_notebooks.py::NotebooksTestCase::test_robot_failure_example 
The command ""if [ $TRAVIS_PULL_REQUEST == false ] && ! [ $TRAVIS_BRANCH == 'master' ]; then py.test tests/units -n2; else travis_wait 20 python setup.py test; fi"" exited with 137.
cache.2
store build cache
0.13s
158.74schange detected (content changed, file is created, or file is deleted):
...
...
uploading archive
Done. Your build exited with 1.
```

### pros

It would make tests pass, but I think ```ExecutePreprocessor.timeout``` would have to be increased more than 900 as on Python-3.5.2 NotebooksTestCase::test_robot_failure_example still fails even though ```travis_wait 20```


### Possible other options or solutions:

- Split out the notebook tests to another ```tests``` run and run 2 stages on Travis, not sure if that is possible.
- Only run the notebook tests on developer local testing

Testing using the environment variable ```TRAVIS=true``` as per https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/environment-variables/#Default-Environment-Variables

Running ***with*** notebook tests takes 304.19 seconds (on my machine)
Running ***without*** notebook tests takes 42.23 seconds (on my machine)

So this is possible in tests/integrations/test_notebooks.py

```
    if os.environ['TRAVIS']:
        print('Not running notebook tests on Travis')
        return [], []

    with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode='w+t', suffix="".ipynb"") as fout:
        args = [""jupyter"", ""nbconvert"",
```

But is it desirable?

- It would make user PR builds faster.
- It would put the onus on the merger to ensure that notebook tests were run if a notebook was added or changed.

So the question is, do notebook tests need to be run on Travis?  Considering
that every tsfresh function called within a notebook probably already has a test
within the tsfresh context, can it be assumed that on Travis the notebook would
pass?  I guess there could be breaking changes in dependencies that could break
notebooks as well.  However seeing as the developers should be running tests
locally themselves all the time before committing one would hope, they will be
running the notebook tests so the notebook tests will still get run.

Not ideal at all, however it does significantly reduce Travis build times and
would remove a lot of wait time from general public PRs.

Anyway thoughts @MaxBenChrist ...",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
