15398,IssueCommentEvent,2015-12-07 09:30:55+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,48069,aburch,9289019,letsencrypt,120655815,162462606,"Luca Beltrame <notifications@github.com> writes:
> @aburch How would you define the ""right"" owner for a directory? The UID of the process?

Hmm, that's not easy to answer.

For myself, I plan to run letsencrypt as a dedicated service user.  So
it can only create files as its own user anyway.  I think that is also
how most distributions expect services to work.

I understand that you also want to provide a fully magic mode.  This is
always hard to get right; the best approximation is probably to use the
owner of the given webroot (if letsencrypt is started as root).  Maybe
provide a command-line option if this is not the case: for example an
admin could have created .../.well-known/acme-challenges manually and
set appropriate permissions which might not match the one for the
webroot itself.  (Though in this case I would expect the admin to not
run letsencrypt as root anyway.)

In any case, I would recommend avoiding chmod/chown.  For root, it
should be possible to to switch user with `os.seteuid` and `os.setegid`
and revert to the original user later.  This avoids calling `chmod` and
`chown` which are potentially unsafe to use.

Ansgar
",{},,User,False
