15479,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-07 14:04:45+00:00,51442999,python-cmd2/cmd2,5621964,WSQi,17161025,python-cmd2,330165650,395432214,"@tleonhardt For suggestions, maybe the [cmd2 Docs](https://cmd2.readthedocs.io/en/latest/integrating.html?highlight=onecmd_plus_hooks) could be updated with more examples.

Looks like the code could be modified to the following without using package's private function:
```python
def main() -> None:
	c = Command()
	if len(sys.argv) > 1:
		c.runcmds_plus_hooks(["" "".join(sys.argv[1:])])
	else:
		c.cmdloop()
```",{},NONE,User,False
15490,IssueCommentEvent,2018-04-18 17:01:23+00:00,51442999,python-cmd2/cmd2,17968842,anselor,17161025,python-cmd2,313826481,382457712,"@tleonhardt Looks like this is a side effect of turning cmd2 into a package. When running cmd2.py directly, it's not running in the context of a package so it can't perform package-local imports. When loading cmd2 externally, it's loading cmd2.py in the context of the package so package-local imports are required.

Two possible solutions I've found:
1 - Run cmd2 as a package:  `$ python3 -m cmd2.cmd2`
Generates this warning:
`/usr/lib/python3.5/runpy.py:125: RuntimeWarning: 'cmd2.cmd2' found in sys.modules after import of package 'cmd2', but prior to execution of 'cmd2.cmd2'; this may result in unpredictable behaviour
  warn(RuntimeWarning(msg))`

2 - Move the code in `__main__` into `main.py` at the top level of the project that just imports and runs cmd2

@kotfu Maybe you have another suggestion for how to deal with this?",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
