15814,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-09 19:16:22+00:00,24642075,sunscrapers/djoser,11322329,apokinsocha,1218240,sunscrapers,114722077,155161310,"Hey Konrad,
No problem at all.
I think the main problem here is that the ""send_email"" (based on the SendEmailViewMixin class on the RegistrationView) function is being called but reference within the view to the djangos email object (in this case EmailMultiAlternatives) is lost, unless it's returned back or modifications are made to the function itself to pass extra kwargs and make some micro-checks (for attachments, bccs or whatever).
These are some of the modifications I had to do initially which I scrapped after more of these kinds of modifications were needed elsewhere. 
ie: 
```msg = self.send_email()
#do something additional with msg, add attachments etc...
msg.send()#not called anymore in the send_email function, but called here in the view```

in this case, it has to be returned from both send_email method from the Mixin class:
    ```def send_email(self, to_email, from_email, context):
        return send_email(to_email, from_email, context, **self.get_send_email_extras())```

as well as in the send_email() function itself.

However the implementation is done, I think the main thing is that the user should simply have either direct or indirect (such as through a class object such as the ""DjangoEmailWrapper"" I posted above) reference/access to the email object to give full control over the contents of the e-mail message where it's being called within the code block, and that it can be easily overridden/updated via super.

I think a combination of this as well as a Mixin class (not so much different than current) could be apt.
I'm not so sure about the signals though, I think that would decouple it a bit too much.
Just my thoughts...",{},,User,False
