15877,IssueCommentEvent,2017-08-04 18:19:03+00:00,81612762,trailofbits/manticore,2467355,mossberg,2314423,trailofbits,246193127,320318954,"Good point! A random thought is if we define a `m.init`, it doesn't
*necessarily* have to have the same semantics as `m.hook(m.entry)`. That
said, a user initialization hook should probably execute after Manticore
has done its initialization (in the case of linux, loading the binary; in
the case of evm, setting up the EVMWorld(?) (@feliam does this sound
right?)), and before Manticore begins executing the program, which is
precisely the semantics of hooking on the first instruction.

In short, I'm in support of only adding an `m.entry` API for now, instead
of a full on `m.init` hook.

However, I can see in the future that we will probably want to add `m.init`
simply as a convenience interface, given that `m.hook(m.entry)` will likely
be a very common pattern for mcore scripts.


On Fri, Aug 4, 2017 at 7:26 AM Yan <notifications@github.com> wrote:

> I like this proposal, including overloading Manticore's constructor. I
> don't think it's a problem to dispatch based on ctor's argument type --
> overloading the ctor is a very common pattern. However, I'm not sure which
> is better -- adding a new hook type or just exposing the entrypoint from
> Manticore.
>
> i.e.:
>
> @m.hook(m.entry)
> def init(state):
>    ...
>
> vs
>
> @m.init
> def init(state):
>   ...
>
> I feel like exporting the entrypoint is a lighter-weight change to the API
> that doesn't create a new hook type.
>
> —
