16291,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-13 12:25:39+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,38294,mdboom,897180,scikit-image,26966266,156418692,"I developed freetypy because freetype-py is ctypes based, and we have a no ctypes policy in matplotlib for reasons of portability to secure platforms.  Also, some things are just really hard to do with freetype and ctypes (like outline decomposition) that we needed to do for matplotlib.

While the work to integrate this back into matplotlib is ongoing, I think freetypy is ready for use by others without too much pain.  If you just want to render a string to a numpy array, the pieces are all there.

Of course, unless you want to hardcode the font, you also need a font lookup mechanism, which freetype doesn't provide.  There are more nascent wrappers for fontconfig at http://github.com/matplotlib/fcpy that we also plan to use for matplotlib in the near future.

That said, all this is fairly low-level and may not be necessary if you just want basic text layout and your font lookup requirements are simple.  As much as I'd like to promote my own stuff, for simple uses, cairo/pango may be a better option, and is also cross platform.  You can get an image buffer out and reinterpret it as a numpy array and you're golden.

@nizamov: As for your concerns about freetype being dead on Windows, that's not the case.  I suspect you found the freetype package from the GnuWin32 project which is a fairly inactive, if not dead, project.  Christoph Gohlke, MSYS2 and Anadonda all provide newer versions of FreeType, and FreeType is still officially supported on Windows and should be for the forseeable future.  It's the linchpin of much cross-platform software (including Firefox), so I don't think it's going away.

",{},,User,False
16292,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-01 07:58:25+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,263366,emmanuelle,897180,scikit-image,157345554,222920265,"@jni indeed the issue with overlapping blobs should not hold the PR, since it does not change the behavior of the function. However, it'd be curious to hear from people using this function at the moment, since this issue with overlapping blobs sounds like to a serious limitation (I was planning to use the function on my tomography images, but if overlapping blobs are not correctly detected I cannot really use it). 

