16343,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-24 19:44:37+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,90008,hmaarrfk,897180,scikit-image,320549255,407528478,"Just leaving this here for future reference:
On my xeon desktop, (hopefully the GPU isn't being used), opencv can get the conversion of a 10MP image in under 5ms. The code here gets around 200ms+.

This is likely due to the fact that opencv has really [optimized code](https://github.com/opencv/opencv/blob/3.4/modules/imgproc/src/demosaicing.cpp) that is really dense and difficult to read (even more than mine here) though it seems to be discussed [here in german](http://www.md-it.de/opensource.html).

I guess I'm not aiming for that amount of optimization, but it would be nice if maybe it wasn't a factor of 40 slower....

They also have some edge aware demosaicing that I never had time to look into implementing.

Pros about opencv:
  * Optimized with SIMD using SSE2 (and apparently even NEON optimization for ARM).
  * This part of the code is largely compatible with numpy so you can keep using numpy without explicitely changing to opencv matricies.

Pros about a more pythonic approach:
  * Ideally it would be more readable.
  * Naturally handle more than just uint8 and uint16 data types.

I have a feeling that one of the reasons why the proposed python version is so much slower is that the data must go through the large array multiple times for each channel.
Somehow, the opencv code goes through this in a single loop. That german link seems to explain things quite well, and can probably be parsed by somebody determined using google translate.",{},MEMBER,User,False
