16371,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-26 10:27:18+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,492549,jni,897180,scikit-image,173031661,242693938,"Hi @hgueziri!

Thanks for your PR!

My first instinct, though, is that this method is just too new to come into scikit-image. Other core members should chime in, but in my view the idea behind scikit-image is to provide established algorithms. We don't have a hard citation limit like scikit-learn does, but something that hasn't even been published yet is pretty risky!

As such, I would recommend that you put this in your own repo, and make an announcement on our mailing list — I'm sure many would be interested in trying it out! Then, if a bunch of people find it useful, we can revisit it.

As to the code itself, I had a quick look, and my major piece of advice is that you dramatically shorten the functions — you should aim for around 25 lines of code in a function. This isn't a hard limit, but a guideline to ensure that code is broadly readable and understandable.

I'll leave a couple of smaller comments on the code itself.

Also, if you haven't published to PyPI before, it's pretty easy! Have a look at the official guide here:
https://packaging.python.org/distributing/
That will make it really easy for others to find and use this method.",{},,User,False
