16542,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-08 18:02:44+00:00,5244012,jpype-project/jpype,29045329,Thrameos,41196344,jpype-project,308987823,411498082,"Okay so if that is the case we would need to modify `PyJPMethod` to have a `getattr()` looking for `__annotation__` request.  It would then need to get to check the method overload list and see if it has only one overload.  If there is one overload then it would return a dictionary with contents `arg#` and `return`.  If it has multiple it would return the type as being variable arguments with just generic object.  If all the return types of the overloads match it can return that type otherwise it would specify a generic object.  

It is likely best if we use a python hook rather than trying to code this in C++.  It would be a pain to debug and very inflexible otherwise.  We use `setResource` to define hooks for things like setting up classes and creating objects.  Thus the first step would be to add a resource hook and the getattr that intercepts the request for `__annotation__`.   We will need to convert the method id into a list of java.reflect.Method. 

I am not sure how often this code will get hit.  If it gets hit often we may want to set up a cache like the `toString` in `PyJPField`.   The hook can then scan the overloads and produce the required dict.

I am on vacation this week and wont be able to look into it deeply.  We should work from the devel branch as that has a cleaned up code base.  The only problem I see if we need to make sure it doesn't trigger the `__get__` request otherwise the logic detecting attempts to call a method without an object will trigger an exception.
",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
16554,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-23 19:55:07+00:00,25611422,openaddresses/machine,382136,NelsonMinar,6895392,openaddresses,209625296,282102050,"I'm glad you're working on this. I wrote a big chunk of machine code and even I struggle to develop on it now. Last time I ended up creating a whole Virtualbox VM just so I could run Chef to install stuff so I could then develop. Our code isn't even that complex; GDAL is the only sort of tricky library there. But the way the development environment assumes something much like the Chef production environment makes development harder.

So I like the idea of making it simpler to get a development environment going. I also agree with the principle that the three environments (dev, CI, prod) should have as much in common as possible, including the package management.

I have no opinion on Vagrant vs Docker vs Chef, except that Chef seems to be awfully confusing every time I use it. Also the Chef setup we have now doesn't have an isolated environment for the development machine (hence my Virtualbox setup.)

400MB seems like an awfully big image. For comparison I'm seeing numbers like 80MB for a small Ubuntu Docker setup with a simple app like `nano`.",{},,User,False
