16851,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-14 19:29:51+00:00,68483365,graphql-python/graphene-django,2406542,adamdonahue,15002022,graphql-python,221652205,294220055,"I intended to close this, my mistake.

This is, indeed, the approach we're taking, but one unfortunate thing is that it appears non-trivial to dynamically determine the typing spread the query is using from a `resolve` call.  (I'm not even sure it makes sense within the context of GraphQL to allow for that.)

That is, if we have three types:

```
class A:
    name

class B(A):
    bSpecificField

class C(A)
    cSpecificField
```

I can use:

```
{
    items: {
        ... on B {
            name
            bSpecificField
        }
        ... on C {
            name
            cSpecificField
        }
    }
}
```

but I cannot appear to use:

```
{
    items: {
        ... on A {
            name
        }
    }
}
```

I mean, I suppose I could do this if I knew the query was asking for A when resolving the classes, but I'm not convinced this is the right approach.

A second interesting wrinkle is that determining the type of objects returned in a union seems to be only possibly by introspecting those objects themselves, or by exposing a field specifically stating that type, as in:

```
{
    items: {
       ... on B {
           type       # Always ""B""
           name
       }
    }
}
```    

These are minor items, and I only began looking at GraphQL yesterday so it's quite possible I'm ignorant at this point to more sophisticated (or recommended, at least) approaches.",{},,User,False
