18258,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-25 17:05:35+00:00,10062583,GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-datastore,1728051,pcostell,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,178965833,249433205,"It depends on how you create your employee. When you create a new `employee = Employee(...)`, if you provide a `parent=db.Key(...)`, then this parent defines the entity group. If you never specify a parent in the constructor, then each entity is in its own entity group.

Where you can run into problems with this method is that queries across entity groups are eventually consistent. [This doc](https://cloud.google.com/datastore/docs/articles/balancing-strong-and-eventual-consistency-with-google-cloud-datastore/) goes into detail about it and I highly recommend taking a read through. In your employee example, if each employee is in its own entity group (no `parent=` specified) then any queries across all employees (for example `SELECT * from Employee ORDER BY hire_date`) may not be up-to-date.",{},,User,False
