18443,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-06 00:53:47+00:00,99273369,NeurodataWithoutBorders/pynwb,10999845,oruebel,12140348,NeurodataWithoutBorders,271322065,342020576,"@lfrank using the current electrode table design, I can see a couple of options here:

1. The simplest solution may be to just add a new entry (i.e., row) to the electrode table for each unique position of the electrode (while keeping the ID for the electrode the same). Since the location and other metadata of the electrode changes this approach seems reasonable. This would allow you to reference the electrode uniquely based on its position and at the same time allow you to extract all positions by looking up all electrodes with the same ID. This would work with what we have right now, i.e., based on what you described you might also want to reference an Epoch either from the ElectrodeGroup (assuming that multiple electrodes move together) or from the electrode table. 
2. Similar to what you suggested, you could also create multiple electrode tables, each being associated with an Epoch. 

Technically, I think you could test either of these approaches fairly easily right now with some simple extensions. For 1. you just need to add a link to an Epoch to the ElectrodeGroup or ElectrodeTable and. For 2. you would just need to add an attribute with a reference to an Epoch to the ElectrodeTable and add multiple electrode tables to the file. 

@ajtritt any thoughts. ",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
